literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both physical and digital phantoms have their own advantages and limitations
 according to the use-cases.
 The most important difference between them is that even with a well defined
 physical phantom, it is not possible to provide such a perfect ground truth
 because of, for example, mechanical limitations or the statistical nature
 of the diffusion process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "phantoms-compilation-for-tractography"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, digital phantoms are the only way to obtain a dMRI data with a real
 ground truth.
 That's why we have decided to use a digital phantom for this work.
 We will discuss the selected phantom in the next chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
State-of-the-art
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multiple Fascicle Reconstruction Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Limitations of DTI came when several fiber populations are present in a
 voxel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffusion Spectrum Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffusion Spectrum Imaging (DSI) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DSI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a MRI technique that employs the diffusion propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to describe the diffusion process in each voxel.
 It uses Fourier relationship between a, sufficient dense, cartesian sample
 of the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in the q-space and the diffusion probability density function such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)=\mathcal{F}^{-1}\left\{ S\left(\vec{\mathbf{q}},t\right)\right\} =\int_{\mathbb{Q}^{3}}S\left(\vec{\mathbf{q}},t\right)exp\left(i\vec{\mathbf{q}}\cdot\vec{\mathbf{r}}\right)d\vec{\mathbf{q}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the 3D inverse Fourier transform.
 Then, the dODF 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 can be reconstructed by radially projecting 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi\left(\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)=\intop_{0}^{\infty}p\left(r\hat{\mathbf{r}},t\right)dr,\label{eq:diffusion-propagator-to-dODF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbf{\mathbb{R}_{0}^{+}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{r}}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 DSI can detect the multiple fascicle orientation within a voxel.
 However, it requires strong gradients (
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq b\leq20,000$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $s/mm^{2}$
\end_inset

) as well as long acquisition time to measure hundreads of directions and
 b-values.
 That's why is of real interest in clinical applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Q-Ball Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Q-Ball Imaging (QBI) is a method that employ the Funk-Radon transform
 (FRT) on HARDI derived data to obtain a diffusion ODF (dODF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi\left(\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right)=\int_{\varOmega\left(\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right)}S\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}},t\right)d\hat{\mathbf{q}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varOmega\left(\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right)=\left\{ \hat{\mathbf{q}}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}\,|\,\hat{\mathbf{q}}\perp\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{q}}=\mathbf{q}/q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}\in\mathbb{Q}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 FRT uses the fact that the diffusion signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}},t\right)$
\end_inset

 is maximal in the directions perpendicular to the underlying fascicles,
 see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:funk-radon-transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-funk-radon-transform.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:funk-radon-transform"

\end_inset

Illustration of the FRT that QBI uses to reconstruct the dODF using the
 diffusion MRI measured signal.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dODF can properly represent the presence and orientation of multiple
 crossing fascicles.
 However, the resulted dODF is artificially smooth and inflated compared
 to the true diffusion ODF.
 Problematically, this same feature causes QBI to poorly distinguish fibers
 crossing at tight angles.
 Some modifications and generalizations to QBI have been published to try
 to achieve most of the QBI limitations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-SWT,QBI-CSA,GQI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-SWT"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed a spherical wavelet transform to sharpen and denoise the dODF.
 Additionally, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-CSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 the dODF is normalized using a solid angle factor.
 Finally, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GQI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 a generalization of the q-ball imaging was proposed using a direct transform
 of the raw signal.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffusion Orientation Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Diffusion Orientation Transform (DOT) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a technique that provideds a direct estimation of displacement probability
 surfaces at each voxel from the dMRI data.
 DOT uses the Fourier relationship between the signal attenuation and the
 diffusion propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)=\oint_{\mathbf{\mathbb{S}^{2}}}\int_{0}^{\infty}E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)exp\left(-2\pi irq\hat{\mathbf{q}}^{T}\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)q^{2}dqd\hat{\mathbf{q}},\label{eq:propagator-signal-fourier-relationship}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=q\hat{\mathbf{q}}\in\mathbb{Q}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mathbf{r}}=r\hat{\mathbf{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 attenuates mono-exponentially, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)=exp\left(-4\pi^{2}tq^{2}D\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the apparent diffusion coefficient or diffusivity profile.
 In other words, DOT transforms water diffusivity profiles into displacement
 probability profiles.
 Finally, the dODF can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)$
\end_inset

 by means of the radial projection as in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diffusion-propagator-to-dODF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, DOT faces some limitations regarding the HARDI sampling schemes
 with finite support, truncated spherical harmonics and the mono-exponential
 attenuation.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT-revisited"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed an extension of the DOT method that mitigates these limitations.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\vec{\mathbf{q}},t\right)=exp\left(-4\pi^{2}tq^{2}D\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)\right),\label{eq:mono-exponential-attenuation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the apparent diffusion coefficient or diffusivity profile.
 In other words, DOT transforms water diffusivity profiles into displacement
 probability profiles.
 In addition, DOT uses the following expasion in terms of spherical wave
 functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
exp\left(-2\pi irq\hat{\mathbf{q}}^{T}\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)=\sum_{l=0}^{l_{max}}\sum_{m=-l}^{l}\left(-i\right)^{l}j_{l}\left(2\pi rp\right)Y_{lm}\left(\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)Y_{lm}^{*}\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right),\label{eq:plane-wave-expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{lm}$
\end_inset

 are respectively the spherical Bessel function of the first kind and the
 spherical harmonic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 can be computed using Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mono-exponential-attenuation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which can be used to compute
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{l}\left(r,\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)=,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which can be expanded in terms of spherical harmonics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{l}\left(r,\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)=\sum_{l^{'}=0}^{l_{max}}\sum_{m=-l^{'}}^{l^{'}}a_{l^{'}m^{'}}Y_{l^{'}m^{'}}\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finally, the dODF can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)$
\end_inset

 by means of the radial projection as in Equation 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inserta ecuacion 2.16 de la tesis de Rick
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
DOT faces some limitations regarding the HARDI sampling schemes with finite
 support, truncated spherical harmonics and the mono-exponential attenuation.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT-revisited"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed an extension of the DOT method that mitigates these limitations.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Symmetric Tensor Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Symmetric Tensor Decomposition (STD) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "STD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 combines the fODF reconstruction of SD and the orientations approximation
 into one optimization problem.
 It approximates the fODF using an equivalent lower-rank approximation by
 a symmetric tensor decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(\mathbf{v}\right)\simeq\sum_{i=1}^{\widetilde{r}}\gamma_{i}f_{i}^{d}=\sum_{i=1}^{\widetilde{r}}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{v}\right)^{d},\;\;\;\widetilde{r}<r,\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{3},\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining this with the SD approach of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spherical-deconvolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we obtain the following non-linear optimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\alpha_{j}}{min}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\bigl\Vert S\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},b\right)-S_{0}\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\cdot\boldsymbol{v}\right)^{d}R\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},\mathbf{v}\right)d\mathbf{v}\bigr\Vert^{2}\label{eq:symmetric-tensor-decomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spherical Deconvolution Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
S
\series default
pherical 
\series bold
D
\series default
econvolution (SD) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is one of the most popular techniques to recover the principal diffusion
 directions from the dMRI data.
 SD considers the HARDI signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 as the convolution of the response function, which is an axially symmetric
 kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that represents a single-fiber response, with the expected true 
\series bold
f
\series default
iber 
\series bold
O
\series default
rientation 
\series bold
D
\series default
istribution 
\series bold
F
\series default
unction 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, known as fODF.
 Given the measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along all the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gradient directions , the fODF can be reconstructed by solving the following
 optimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{F}{min}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\bigl\Vert S\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},b\right)-S_{0}\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}F\left(\mathbf{v}\right)R\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},\mathbf{v}\right)d\mathbf{v}\bigr\Vert^{2},\label{eq:spherical-deconvolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-spherical-deconvolution-a.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\;\;\;$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-spherical-deconvolution-b.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
