\begin_layout Subsection
Tractometry Pipelines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the literature contains a wide variety of techniques for resolving
 crossing fascicles, most of these methods provide information only about
 the orientation of crossing fascicles but not about the microstructure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classical measures like FA with DTI are very sensitive to white matter anomalies
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add ref 14,15,16 from Mitacs
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 However, it is now very well-known that FA is not specific, i.e.
 several different microstructure scenarios may lead to the same FA, see
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:different-FA-scenarios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example, the following scenarios could lead to the same FA of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.4$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add refs 19,20,21,22,23 of Mitacs
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Crossing fiber voxel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Single fiber population demyelinating (going from FA of ~0.7 to 0.4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Voxel that has partial volume with a CSF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Isotropic freewater from neuroinflammation contaminating the voxel leading
 to a drop of a high FA voxel to a low FA of 0.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-different-FA-scenarios.png
	scale 25

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:different-FA-scenarios"

\end_inset

Limitations of DTI and potential of advanced diffusion MRI modeling for
 improved brain connectivity mapping and track-specific white matter tissue
 assessment.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is thus clear that each fascicle that traverses a voxel should have its
 diffusivities (fascicle-MD, fascicle-AD and fascicle-RD) and fiber-specific
 FA (fascicle-FA), which is recently also coined fixel-based FA (a fixel
 is a fiber element) 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add ref 24 from Mitacs
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Fixel-based analysis needs to be translated to neurodegenerative diseases
 and this is still a very important open problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Mention that most of them do not give information about micro-structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Mention the constrains of using DTI and fODF.
 Mention that MTM could solve the problem.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Objective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our main objective is to setup a robust (to noise and crossing fibers) pipeline
 for the automatic extraction and statistical analysis of track-specific
 white matter measures.
 Estimated fixel-based orientations and metrics will be used as indirect
 proxies to axon loss, demyelination and neuroinflammation.
 In particular, the fixel-based radial diffusivity (fixel-RD) could help
 to account for demyelination in MS patients as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "profilometry"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In order to achieve this, there are two main problems that have to be addressed
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Fast, accurate and robust to noise and fiber crossing voxel-wise estimation
 of fixel-based metrics in diffusion MRI signal using the multi-tensor based
 method MRDS.
 This demands to improve the model selector step in MRDS to better estimate
 the number of tensors per voxel.
 Besides, parallezation of MRDS is necessary to ensure fast fitting of the
 MRDS method to the diffusion MRI signals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Multimetric analysis of white matter tracts in different fiber bundles.
 It's required to adapt the tractometry_flow pipeline to integrate the MRDS
 metrics into the statistical analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although automating tract-profiling and metrics for white matter could improve
 brain connectivity mapping through crossing fiber regions and pathologies
 in the human brain, we will focus to demostrate the application of our
 pipeline to multiple sclerosis (MS) disease.
\end_layout

